  ('jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles-q05', 'jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles', 'Two parallel lines have slopes that are:', 'Negative reciprocals', 'Opposite in sign', 'Zero', 'Equal', 'D', 'Parallel lines have equal slopes.', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles-q06', 'jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles', 'The distance of the point (0, 0) from the line 3x + 4y - 10 = 0 is:', '1', '2', '10', '5', 'B', 'Distance = |0 + 0 - 10|/sqrt(9 + 16) = 10/5 = 2.', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles-q07', 'jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles', 'A line is tangent to a circle when its distance from the centre equals the:', 'Diameter', 'Circumference', 'Radius', 'Zero', 'C', 'Tangency requires the centre-to-line distance to equal the radius.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles-q08', 'jee-mathematics-straight-lines-circles', 'The equation of a line with slope 2 and y-intercept 3 is:', 'y = 3x + 2', 'y = 2x - 3', 'y = 2x + 3', 'x = 2y + 3', 'C', 'Using y = mx + c with m = 2 and c = 3 gives y = 2x + 3.', 7),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q01', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'The limit as x approaches 0 of sin(x)/x is:', '0', 'Infinite', '1', 'Undefined', 'C', 'This is a standard limit equal to 1.', 0),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q02', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'A function f is continuous at x = a if the limit of f as x approaches a equals:', '0', 'Infinity', 'f prime of a', 'f(a)', 'D', 'Continuity at a requires the limit to equal the function value f(a).', 1),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q03', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'The function |x| at x = 0 is:', 'Continuous but not differentiable', 'Undefined', 'Discontinuous', 'Differentiable', 'A', '|x| is continuous everywhere but has a corner at 0, so it is not differentiable there.', 2),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q04', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'The derivative of x³ with respect to x is:', 'x²', '3x²', '3x', 'x³/3', 'B', 'By the power rule, d/dx of x³ is 3x².', 3),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q05', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'The limit as x approaches 0 of (e^x - 1)/x is:', '0', 'e', '1', 'Infinite', 'C', 'This standard limit equals 1.', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q06', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'Differentiability of a function at a point implies that it is:', 'Discontinuous there', 'Unbounded', 'Continuous there', 'Constant', 'C', 'Differentiability implies continuity, though the converse is false.', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q07', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'The derivative of the product uv is:', 'u prime v + u v prime', 'u prime v prime', 'u prime v - u v prime', 'u v', 'A', 'The product rule gives (uv) prime = u prime v + u v prime.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-limits-continuity-q08', 'jee-mathematics-limits-continuity', 'A limit of the indeterminate form 0/0 can often be evaluated using:', 'The power rule', 'Integration', 'The product rule', 'L''Hopital''s rule', 'D', 'L''Hopital''s rule resolves 0/0 and infinity/infinity forms by differentiating top and bottom.', 7),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q01', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The integral of x² with respect to x is:', '2x + C', 'x³ + C', 'x³/3 + C', '3x² + C', 'C', 'By the power rule, the integral of x² is x³/3 + C.', 0),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q02', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The integral of 1/x with respect to x is:', '-1/x² + C', 'ln|x| + C', 'x + C', '1 + C', 'B', 'The integral of 1/x is the natural logarithm ln|x| + C.', 1),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q03', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The integration by parts formula is the integral of u dv equals:', 'the integral of u times the integral of dv', 'uv plus the integral of v du', 'uv times the integral of du', 'uv minus the integral of v du', 'D', 'Integration by parts: integral of u dv = uv minus the integral of v du.', 2),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q04', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The definite integral of 2x from 0 to 3 is:', '6', '18', '9', '3', 'C', 'The antiderivative is x², so the value is 9 - 0 = 9.', 3),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q05', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The integral over a symmetric interval (-a to a) of an odd function is:', '2 times the integral from 0 to a', 'Infinite', 'a²', 'Zero', 'D', 'An odd function integrates to zero over a symmetric interval.', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q06', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The integral of e^x with respect to x is:', 'e^x + C', 'ln(x) + C', 'e^x / x + C', 'x e^x + C', 'A', 'The integral of e^x is itself, e^x + C.', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q07', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus links integration to:', 'Multiplication', 'Factoring', 'Differentiation', 'Series summation', 'C', 'It states the definite integral equals the change in an antiderivative, linking it to differentiation.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-integration-q08', 'jee-mathematics-integration', 'The recommended order for choosing u in integration by parts is given by:', 'FOIL', 'ILATE', 'PEMDAS', 'SOHCAHTOA', 'B', 'ILATE orders functions (inverse, log, algebraic, trig, exponential) for choosing u.', 7),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q01', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The dot product of two perpendicular vectors is:', 'Maximum', 'Negative', 'Zero', 'Their product of magnitudes', 'C', 'a dot b = |a||b|cos(90) = 0 for perpendicular vectors.', 0),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q02', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The cross product of two parallel vectors is:', 'The zero vector', 'Maximum', 'A scalar', 'Their sum', 'A', 'a cross b = |a||b|sin(0) = 0 for parallel vectors.', 1),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q03', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The magnitude of the vector (3, 0, 4) is:', '7', '25', '12', '5', 'D', 'Magnitude = sqrt(9 + 0 + 16) = sqrt(25) = 5.', 2),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q04', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The scalar triple product of three vectors gives the volume of a:', 'Sphere', 'Cylinder', 'Parallelepiped', 'Cone', 'C', 'The scalar triple product a dot (b cross c) equals the parallelepiped volume.', 3),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q05', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'Three vectors are coplanar when their scalar triple product is:', 'Positive', 'Negative', 'Zero', 'One', 'C', 'Coplanarity makes the scalar triple product (the volume) zero.', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q06', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The direction ratios of the normal to the plane 2x + 3y - z + 5 = 0 are:', '(1, 1, 1)', '(2, 3, -1)', '(5, 3, -1)', '(2, 3, 5)', 'B', 'The coefficients of x, y, z give the normal''s direction ratios (2, 3, -1).', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q07', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The cross product of two vectors yields a vector that is:', 'Parallel to both', 'In the same plane', 'Perpendicular to both', 'Always zero', 'C', 'The cross product is perpendicular to both original vectors.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-vectors-3d-q08', 'jee-mathematics-vectors-3d', 'The angle between two planes equals the angle between their:', 'Normals', 'Areas', 'Intercepts', 'Centroids', 'A', 'The angle between two planes is the angle between their normal vectors.', 7),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q01', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'The probability of getting a head in a single toss of a fair coin is:', '0', '0.5', '1', '0.25', 'B', 'A fair coin has two equally likely outcomes, so P(head) = 0.5.', 0),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q02', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'The probability of rolling a number greater than 4 on a fair die is:', '1/6', '1/3', '1/2', '2/3', 'B', 'Favourable outcomes are 5 and 6, so probability = 2/6 = 1/3.', 1),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q03', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'For two independent events, P(A and B) equals:', 'P(A) + P(B)', 'P(A) times P(B)', 'P(A) - P(B)', 'P(A)/P(B)', 'B', 'Independent events satisfy P(A and B) = P(A) times P(B).', 2),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q04', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'The sum of the probabilities of an event and its complement is:', '0', '1', '0.5', '2', 'B', 'P(E) + P(E complement) = 1.', 3),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q05', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'For mutually exclusive events A and B, P(A or B) equals:', 'P(A) + P(B)', 'P(A) + P(B) - P(A and B)', 'P(A) times P(B)', '1', 'A', 'Mutually exclusive events cannot both occur, so P(A or B) = P(A) + P(B).', 4),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q06', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'The conditional probability P(A given B) is defined as:', 'P(B)/P(A)', 'P(A and B)/P(B)', 'P(A and B) times P(B)', 'P(A)/P(B)', 'B', 'P(A given B) = P(A and B)/P(B).', 5),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q07', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'The mean of a binomial distribution with parameters n and p is:', 'n/p', 'npq', 'p/n', 'np', 'D', 'The mean of a binomial distribution is np.', 6),
  ('jee-mathematics-probability-q08', 'jee-mathematics-probability', 'Drawing two aces in succession from a deck without replacement involves events that are:', 'Independent', 'Dependent', 'Mutually exclusive', 'Impossible', 'B', 'Without replacement, the first draw changes the second''s probability, so events are dependent.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q01', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'What is the dimensional formula of force?', 'M L T^-1', 'M L^2 T^-2', 'M L T^-2', 'M L^-1 T^-2', 'C', 'Force = mass times acceleration, giving M L T^-2.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q02', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'Which quantity has the same dimensions as energy?', 'Work', 'Power', 'Force', 'Momentum', 'A', 'Work and energy both have dimensions M L^2 T^-2.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q03', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'The dimensional formula of pressure is:', 'M L T^-2', 'M L^-1 T^-2', 'M L^2 T^-2', 'M L^-2 T^-1', 'B', 'Pressure is force per area: M L T^-2 divided by L^2 gives M L^-1 T^-2.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q04', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'How many base quantities are there in the SI system?', 'Seven', 'Six', 'Five', 'Eight', 'A', 'The SI system defines seven base quantities.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q05', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'In the product Z = A^2 B / C, if each of A, B, C has 1 percent error, the maximum error in Z is:', '2 percent', '3 percent', '4 percent', '6 percent', 'C', 'Fractional errors add as 2 times 1 plus 1 plus 1, giving 4 percent.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q06', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'Which of the following is dimensionless?', 'Strain', 'Force', 'Velocity', 'Density', 'A', 'Strain is a ratio of like lengths, so it has no dimensions.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q07', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'The number of significant figures in 0.00450 is:', 'Two', 'Three', 'Four', 'Five', 'B', 'Leading zeros do not count; the figures 4, 5 and trailing 0 give three.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-units-dimensions-q08', 'jee-physics-units-dimensions', 'The dimensional formula of power is:', 'M L T^-3', 'M L^2 T^-2', 'M L^2 T^-3', 'M L^2 T^-1', 'C', 'Power is energy per time: M L^2 T^-2 divided by T gives M L^2 T^-3.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q01', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'The upthrust on a body submerged in a fluid equals the weight of:', 'The body', 'The remaining fluid', 'The container', 'The displaced fluid', 'D', 'By Archimedes'' principle, upthrust equals the weight of the fluid displaced.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q02', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'Bernoulli''s theorem is a statement of conservation of:', 'Energy', 'Momentum', 'Mass', 'Charge', 'A', 'Bernoulli''s equation expresses conservation of energy per unit volume in a flowing fluid.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q03', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'The hydrostatic pressure at depth h in a liquid of density rho is given by:', 'rho times g divided by h', 'h divided by rho times g', 'rho times g times h', 'rho divided by g times h', 'C', 'Gauge pressure increases linearly with depth as rho times g times h.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q04', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'The principle behind a hydraulic lift is:', 'Archimedes'' principle', 'Bernoulli''s theorem', 'Pascal''s law', 'Stokes'' law', 'C', 'Pascal''s law transmits applied pressure equally throughout a confined fluid.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q05', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'An object floats when its average density is:', 'Greater than the fluid', 'Equal to zero', 'Equal to gravity', 'Less than the fluid', 'D', 'If the body density is less than the fluid density, the upthrust supports it and it floats.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q06', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'By the equation of continuity, when a pipe narrows the fluid speed:', 'Decreases', 'Increases', 'Stays constant', 'Becomes zero', 'B', 'Since area times velocity is constant, a smaller area means a higher speed.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q07', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'The viscous drag on a small sphere moving slowly through a fluid is described by:', 'Pascal''s law', 'Stokes'' law', 'Boyle''s law', 'Hooke''s law', 'B', 'Stokes'' law gives the drag as 6 pi eta r v on a small sphere.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-fluid-mechanics-q08', 'jee-physics-fluid-mechanics', 'A body falling through a viscous fluid attains terminal velocity when:', 'Drag exceeds weight', 'Acceleration is maximum', 'Buoyancy is zero', 'Net force is zero', 'D', 'Terminal velocity is reached when drag plus buoyancy balance weight, so net force is zero.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q01', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'The coefficient of volume expansion equals how many times the linear coefficient?', 'One', 'Two', 'Four', 'Three', 'D', 'Volume expansion gamma equals three times the linear coefficient alpha.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q02', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'Heat absorbed during a phase change at constant temperature is called:', 'Specific heat', 'Latent heat', 'Thermal capacity', 'Calorific value', 'B', 'Latent heat is the energy for a phase change at constant temperature.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q03', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'The power radiated by a black body is proportional to which power of its absolute temperature?', 'First', 'Fourth', 'Third', 'Second', 'B', 'By the Stefan-Boltzmann law, radiated power is proportional to T to the fourth.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q04', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'Heat needed to raise 2 kg of water by 10 degrees C (c = 4200 J per kg K) is:', '8400 J', '42000 J', '84000 J', '21000 J', 'C', 'Q = m c dT = 2 times 4200 times 10 = 84000 J.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q05', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'Newton''s law of cooling states the cooling rate is proportional to:', 'The body''s volume', 'The temperature excess', 'The square of temperature', 'The surface colour', 'B', 'For small differences, cooling rate is proportional to the excess temperature over surroundings.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q06', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'Heat transfer through a solid metal rod occurs mainly by:', 'Conduction', 'Convection', 'Radiation', 'Advection', 'A', 'In solids heat moves by conduction without bulk movement of matter.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q07', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'In calorimetry, the basic principle assumes that heat lost equals:', 'Zero', 'Work done', 'Twice the heat gained', 'Heat gained', 'D', 'With no loss to surroundings, heat lost by the hot body equals heat gained by the cold body.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-thermal-properties-q08', 'jee-physics-thermal-properties', 'As temperature rises, Wien''s law says the wavelength of peak emission:', 'Increases', 'Stays the same', 'Decreases', 'Becomes infinite', 'C', 'Wien''s law states the peak wavelength is inversely proportional to temperature, so it decreases.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q01', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'The average translational kinetic energy of a gas molecule depends only on:', 'Pressure', 'Temperature', 'Volume', 'Molar mass', 'B', 'Average translational KE is (3/2) k T, depending only on temperature.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q02', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'The rms speed of a gas is proportional to the square root of:', 'M divided by T', 'T divided by M', 'T times M', 'Pressure', 'B', 'v_rms equals the square root of 3 R T over M, so it varies as the root of T over M.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q03', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'The number of degrees of freedom of a monatomic ideal gas is:', 'Two', 'Five', 'Three', 'Six', 'C', 'A monatomic gas has only three translational degrees of freedom.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q04', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'The ratio Cp over Cv (gamma) for a diatomic gas is:', '1.33', '1.67', '1.40', '1.50', 'C', 'With f = 5, gamma = 1 + 2/5 = 1.40 for a diatomic gas.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q05', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'Which speed is the largest for a gas at a given temperature?', 'Most probable speed', 'Average speed', 'Root mean square speed', 'All are equal', 'C', 'The speeds rank as most probable less than average less than rms.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q06', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'If the absolute temperature of a gas is doubled, the rms speed becomes:', 'Root two times', 'Double', 'Half', 'Four times', 'A', 'Since v_rms varies as the root of T, doubling T multiplies the speed by root two.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q07', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'Pressure of an ideal gas in kinetic theory is given by:', 'Half rho times v_rms squared', 'rho times v_rms', 'One third rho times v_rms squared', 'rho times g times h', 'C', 'Kinetic theory gives P equal to one third of rho times the mean square speed.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-kinetic-theory-q08', 'jee-physics-kinetic-theory', 'The mean free path of gas molecules increases when:', 'Pressure decreases', 'Pressure increases', 'Molecular size increases', 'Density increases', 'A', 'Lower pressure means fewer molecules per volume, so the mean free path increases.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q01', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Young''s modulus is the ratio of:', 'Strain to stress', 'Force to area', 'Stress to strain', 'Length to force', 'C', 'Young''s modulus is longitudinal stress divided by longitudinal strain.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q02', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'The excess pressure inside a soap bubble of radius R is:', 'Two T over R', 'Four T over R', 'T over R', 'T over two R', 'B', 'A soap bubble has two surfaces, so excess pressure is four T over R.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q03', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Which modulus relates to a change in shape at constant volume?', 'Young''s modulus', 'Shear modulus', 'Bulk modulus', 'Poisson''s ratio', 'B', 'Shear (rigidity) modulus governs shape change without volume change.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q04', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Capillary rise of a liquid in a tube is inversely proportional to the tube''s:', 'Length', 'Density squared', 'Temperature', 'Radius', 'D', 'From the capillary formula, the rise h varies inversely with the tube radius.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q05', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Within the elastic limit, stress is directly proportional to strain. This is:', 'Pascal''s law', 'Bernoulli''s theorem', 'Stokes'' law', 'Hooke''s law', 'D', 'Hooke''s law states stress is proportional to strain within the elastic limit.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q06', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'As temperature increases, the surface tension of a liquid generally:', 'Increases', 'Decreases', 'Stays constant', 'Becomes infinite', 'B', 'Surface tension decreases as temperature rises and vanishes near the critical point.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q07', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Comparing steel and rubber for the same stress, steel is said to be more elastic because it:', 'Stretches more', 'Returns with greater restoring stress', 'Is heavier', 'Has no elastic limit', 'B', 'Steel resists deformation with a larger restoring stress, so it is more elastic than rubber.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension-q08', 'jee-physics-elasticity-surface-tension', 'Mercury in a glass capillary shows a depression because its angle of contact is:', 'Zero', 'Acute', 'Obtuse', 'Exactly ninety degrees', 'C', 'Mercury wets glass poorly, giving an obtuse contact angle and a capillary depression.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q01', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'The centre of mass of a system can be accelerated only by:', 'Internal forces', 'External forces', 'Tension alone', 'No force', 'B', 'Internal forces cancel in pairs, so only external forces move the centre of mass.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q02', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'In which collision is kinetic energy conserved?', 'Perfectly inelastic', 'Inelastic', 'Elastic', 'All collisions', 'C', 'Kinetic energy is conserved only in a perfectly elastic collision.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q03', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'The coefficient of restitution for a perfectly inelastic collision is:', 'Infinite', 'One half', 'One', 'Zero', 'D', 'In a perfectly inelastic collision the bodies stick, giving e equal to zero.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q04', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'In a 1D elastic collision between two equal masses with one at rest, after impact they:', 'Both stop', 'Move together', 'Reverse and speed up', 'Exchange velocities', 'D', 'For equal masses in an elastic collision, the velocities are exchanged.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q05', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'Which quantity is conserved in every type of collision?', 'Kinetic energy', 'Linear momentum', 'Mechanical energy', 'Temperature', 'B', 'Linear momentum is conserved in all collisions when no external force acts.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q06', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'Two masses 2 kg and 3 kg are at x = 0 and x = 5 m. The centre of mass is at:', '2.0 m', '2.5 m', '3.5 m', '3.0 m', 'D', 'x_cm = (2 times 0 + 3 times 5) divided by 5 = 15/5 = 3 m.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q07', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'A shell explodes in mid-air. The centre of mass of the fragments:', 'Stops instantly', 'Moves straight up', 'Follows the original path', 'Reverses direction', 'C', 'Explosion forces are internal, so the centre of mass keeps its original parabolic path.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions-q08', 'jee-physics-centre-of-mass-collisions', 'The coefficient of restitution is the ratio of relative velocity of separation to that of:', 'Approach', 'The centre of mass', 'The heavier body', 'Sound', 'A', 'e is defined as the ratio of separation speed to approach speed along the line of impact.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q01', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'Electromagnetic waves are:', 'Longitudinal', 'Transverse', 'Mechanical', 'Stationary only', 'B', 'The E and B fields oscillate perpendicular to propagation, making EM waves transverse.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q02', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'In an electromagnetic wave the ratio E0 over B0 equals:', 'One', 'The speed of light', 'The permittivity', 'The frequency', 'B', 'For an EM wave in vacuum, the field amplitude ratio E0 over B0 equals c.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q03', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'Which of these EM radiations has the highest frequency?', 'Radio waves', 'Visible light', 'X-rays', 'Gamma rays', 'D', 'Gamma rays have the highest frequency and shortest wavelength in the spectrum.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q04', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'Maxwell introduced which term to make Ampere''s law consistent?', 'Induced EMF', 'Displacement current', 'Eddy current', 'Drift current', 'B', 'The displacement current term let Ampere''s law hold across a charging capacitor.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q05', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'EM waves require which medium to travel?', 'Solid only', 'Liquid only', 'No medium', 'Gas only', 'C', 'EM waves are self-sustaining and propagate through vacuum, needing no medium.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q06', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'Which radiation is used in a microwave oven?', 'X-rays', 'Gamma rays', 'Microwaves', 'Ultraviolet', 'C', 'Microwaves heat food by exciting water molecules.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q07', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'The speed of EM waves in vacuum equals one over the square root of:', 'epsilon0 over mu0', 'mu0 plus epsilon0', 'mu0 over epsilon0', 'mu0 times epsilon0', 'D', 'c equals one over the square root of mu0 times epsilon0.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves-q08', 'jee-physics-electromagnetic-waves', 'EM waves carry both energy and:', 'Mass', 'Charge', 'Momentum', 'Current', 'C', 'EM waves transport momentum and exert radiation pressure on surfaces.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q01', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'Doping silicon with a pentavalent impurity gives a:', 'p-type semiconductor', 'Pure conductor', 'n-type semiconductor', 'Insulator', 'C', 'A pentavalent dopant donates electrons, producing an n-type semiconductor.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q02', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'In a p-type semiconductor the majority carriers are:', 'Electrons', 'Neutrons', 'Protons', 'Holes', 'D', 'Trivalent doping creates holes, which are the majority carriers in p-type material.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q03', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'A p-n junction diode conducts well when it is:', 'At absolute zero', 'Reverse biased', 'Unbiased', 'Forward biased', 'D', 'Forward bias lowers the barrier, so the diode conducts current.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q04', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'Which logic gate gives output 1 only when all inputs are 1?', 'OR', 'AND', 'NOT', 'NOR', 'B', 'An AND gate outputs 1 only when every input is 1.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q05', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'Which pair are called universal gates?', 'AND and OR', 'NOT and OR', 'AND and NOT', 'NAND and NOR', 'D', 'NAND and NOR can each build any other gate, so they are universal.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q06', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'As temperature rises, the conductivity of a pure semiconductor:', 'Increases', 'Decreases', 'Stays constant', 'Drops to zero', 'A', 'Heating frees more charge carriers, so a semiconductor conducts better, unlike a metal.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q07', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'The region of immobile charges at a p-n junction is called the:', 'Conduction band', 'Forbidden gap', 'Valence band', 'Depletion region', 'D', 'Diffusion creates a charge-free depletion region with a built-in potential barrier.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-semiconductors-q08', 'jee-physics-semiconductors', 'A NOT gate is also known as a/an:', 'Buffer', 'Adder', 'Inverter', 'Comparator', 'C', 'A NOT gate inverts its single input, so it is called an inverter.', 7),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q01', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'Why is a high-frequency carrier needed in communication?', 'To reduce noise only', 'To increase mass', 'To slow the signal', 'For efficient radiation by a small antenna', 'D', 'High-frequency carriers radiate efficiently from practical antenna sizes.', 0),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q02', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'In amplitude modulation, which property of the carrier varies?', 'Frequency', 'Amplitude', 'Phase', 'Speed', 'B', 'In AM the carrier amplitude varies in step with the message signal.', 1),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q03', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'Sky-wave propagation uses reflection from the:', 'Ionosphere', 'Ground', 'Ocean', 'Moon', 'A', 'Sky waves are reflected back by the ionosphere for long-distance communication.', 2),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q04', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'To avoid distortion in AM, the modulation index must be kept:', 'Greater than two', 'Less than or equal to one', 'Equal to ten', 'Exactly zero', 'B', 'Over-modulation (index above one) distorts the recovered signal, so it is kept at or below one.', 3),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q05', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'Which block of a communication system removes the carrier to recover the message?', 'Modulator', 'Transmitter', 'Amplifier', 'Demodulator', 'D', 'The demodulator at the receiver extracts the original message from the modulated carrier.', 4),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q06', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'Line-of-sight communication above 40 MHz uses which propagation mode?', 'Ground wave', 'Sky wave', 'Space wave', 'Surface wave', 'C', 'High-frequency signals travel as space waves directly between antennas in line of sight.', 5),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q07', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'The range of a TV tower of height h is approximately proportional to:', 'h', 'One over h', 'h squared', 'The square root of h', 'D', 'Range equals the square root of 2 R h, so it varies as the square root of height.', 6),
  ('jee-physics-communication-systems-q08', 'jee-physics-communication-systems', 'Compared with AM, frequency modulation generally requires:', 'Less bandwidth', 'More bandwidth', 'No bandwidth', 'Zero power', 'B', 'FM occupies a wider band of frequencies than AM for the same signal.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q01', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'Oxidation is best defined as:', 'Gain of electrons', 'Loss of electrons', 'Gain of protons', 'Loss of neutrons', 'B', 'Oxidation is the loss of electrons, raising the oxidation number.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q02', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'The oxidation number of oxygen in most compounds is:', 'Plus two', 'Plus one', 'Zero', 'Minus two', 'D', 'Oxygen usually has an oxidation number of minus two.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q03', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'A reaction where the same element is both oxidised and reduced is called:', 'Combination', 'Disproportionation', 'Displacement', 'Neutralisation', 'B', 'In disproportionation one element in an intermediate state is both oxidised and reduced.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q04', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'The oxidation state of sulphur in H2SO4 is:', 'Plus two', 'Plus four', 'Plus six', 'Minus two', 'C', 'With H at plus one and O at minus two, sulphur balances at plus six.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q05', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'An oxidising agent is a species that:', 'Loses electrons', 'Gains electrons', 'Is itself oxidised', 'Has no charge', 'B', 'An oxidising agent gains electrons and is itself reduced.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q06', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'The oxidation number of an element in its free state is:', 'Minus one', 'Plus one', 'Zero', 'Equal to its group number', 'C', 'A free uncombined element always has an oxidation number of zero.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q07', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'In the half-reaction method in acidic medium, what is added to balance oxygen?', 'OH minus ions', 'Oxygen gas', 'Water molecules', 'Metal ions', 'C', 'Water is added to balance oxygen and then H plus to balance hydrogen in acidic medium.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-redox-reactions-q08', 'jee-chemistry-redox-reactions', 'When zinc is added to copper sulphate solution, zinc is:', 'Reduced', 'Precipitated as metal', 'Unchanged', 'Oxidised', 'D', 'Zinc loses electrons to copper ions, so zinc is oxidised and displaces copper.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q01', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'Colligative properties depend on:', 'Number of solute particles', 'Nature of solute', 'Colour of solute', 'Density of solvent', 'A', 'Colligative properties depend only on the number, not nature, of solute particles.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q02', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'Adding a non-volatile solute to a solvent causes its vapour pressure to:', 'Decrease', 'Increase', 'Stay constant', 'Become zero', 'A', 'By Raoult''s law a non-volatile solute lowers the solvent''s vapour pressure.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q03', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'Molality is defined as moles of solute per:', 'Litre of solution', 'Litre of solvent', 'Mole of solution', 'Kilogram of solvent', 'D', 'Molality is moles of solute per kilogram of solvent.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q04', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'The van''t Hoff factor for a solute that dissociates is:', 'Greater than one', 'Less than one', 'Exactly zero', 'Always one', 'A', 'Dissociation produces more particles, so the van''t Hoff factor exceeds one.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q05', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'Which property is most suitable for finding the molar mass of a polymer?', 'Boiling point elevation', 'Osmotic pressure', 'Freezing point depression', 'Vapour pressure rise', 'B', 'Osmotic pressure is measurable even at low concentration, ideal for large molecules.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q06', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'An ideal solution obeys Raoult''s law and shows mixing enthalpy of:', 'Large positive', 'Large negative', 'Zero', 'Infinite', 'C', 'An ideal solution has zero enthalpy and volume change of mixing.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q07', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'Spreading salt on icy roads works because it:', 'Lowers the freezing point', 'Raises the freezing point', 'Raises vapour pressure', 'Increases density', 'A', 'Salt depresses the freezing point, so the ice melts at a lower temperature.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-solutions-q08', 'jee-chemistry-solutions', 'The osmotic pressure of a dilute solution is given by pi equals:', 'C R T', 'C over R T', 'R T over C', 'C plus R T', 'A', 'For dilute solutions, osmotic pressure pi equals concentration times R times T.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q01', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'The order of a reaction is determined:', 'Experimentally', 'From the balanced equation', 'From molar masses', 'From temperature only', 'A', 'Reaction order is found experimentally, not from the stoichiometric equation.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q02', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'The half-life of a first-order reaction is:', 'Independent of concentration', 'Proportional to concentration', 'Inversely proportional to rate constant squared', 'Always one second', 'A', 'For first order, half-life equals 0.693 over k, independent of concentration.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q03', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'A catalyst increases reaction rate by:', 'Raising temperature', 'Increasing concentration', 'Shifting the equilibrium', 'Lowering the activation energy', 'D', 'A catalyst provides an alternative path with lower activation energy.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q04', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'The Arrhenius equation relates the rate constant to:', 'Pressure', 'Volume', 'Temperature and activation energy', 'Colour', 'C', 'The Arrhenius equation links k to temperature and activation energy.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q05', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'For a first-order reaction, a plot of ln of concentration against time is:', 'A straight line with slope minus k', 'A parabola', 'A hyperbola', 'A horizontal line', 'A', 'First-order kinetics gives a straight line of slope minus k for ln of concentration versus time.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q06', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'The units of the rate constant for a first-order reaction are:', 'Per second', 'Mol per litre per second', 'Litre per mol per second', 'Dimensionless', 'A', 'A first-order rate constant has units of inverse time, that is per second.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q07', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'Molecularity of an elementary reaction is:', 'Always fractional', 'Determined experimentally', 'A small whole number', 'Equal to the order always', 'C', 'Molecularity counts species in an elementary step and is a small whole number.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics-q08', 'jee-chemistry-chemical-kinetics', 'Raising temperature speeds a reaction mainly because it increases the:', 'Activation energy', 'Order of reaction', 'Number of moles', 'Fraction of molecules above the activation energy', 'D', 'Higher temperature raises the fraction of molecules with energy above the activation barrier.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q01', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'The accumulation of molecules at a surface is called:', 'Absorption', 'Sublimation', 'Diffusion', 'Adsorption', 'D', 'Adsorption is the accumulation of a substance at a surface.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q02', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'Physisorption is characterised by:', 'Strong chemical bonds', 'Weak van der Waals forces', 'High specificity', 'Irreversibility', 'B', 'Physisorption involves weak van der Waals forces and low enthalpy.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q03', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'The scattering of light by colloidal particles is called the:', 'Raman effect', 'Brownian effect', 'Doppler effect', 'Tyndall effect', 'D', 'The Tyndall effect is light scattering by colloidal particles.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q04', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'Milk is an example of which type of colloid?', 'Emulsion', 'Aerosol', 'Sol', 'Gel', 'A', 'Milk is an emulsion of liquid fat dispersed in water.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q05', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'According to the Freundlich isotherm, x over m is proportional to pressure raised to:', 'One', 'n', 'One over n', 'Two', 'C', 'The Freundlich isotherm gives x over m proportional to P to the power one over n.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q06', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'Enzymes are best described as:', 'Inorganic catalysts', 'Highly specific biological catalysts', 'Non-catalytic proteins', 'Strong acids', 'B', 'Enzymes are highly specific biological catalysts.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q07', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'According to the Hardy-Schulze rule, coagulating power increases with the ion''s:', 'Charge', 'Mass only', 'Colour', 'Volume', 'A', 'Higher ion charge gives greater coagulating power by the Hardy-Schulze rule.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry-q08', 'jee-chemistry-surface-chemistry', 'A heterogeneous catalyst differs from reactants in its:', 'Colour', 'Physical phase', 'Mass', 'Charge', 'B', 'A heterogeneous catalyst is in a different phase, usually a solid acting on gases or liquids.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q01', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'Alkali metals belong to which group of the periodic table?', 'Group 1', 'Group 2', 'Group 17', 'Group 18', 'A', 'Alkali metals are the Group 1 elements with one valence s electron.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q02', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'The common oxidation state of alkaline earth metals is:', 'Plus two', 'Plus one', 'Plus three', 'Minus one', 'A', 'Group 2 metals lose two electrons to show a plus two state.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q03', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'Which element shows a diagonal relationship with magnesium?', 'Sodium', 'Potassium', 'Lithium', 'Calcium', 'C', 'Lithium resembles magnesium through the diagonal relationship.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q04', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'The flame colour imparted by sodium is:', 'Lilac', 'Brick red', 'Green', 'Golden yellow', 'D', 'Sodium gives a characteristic golden yellow flame colour.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q05', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'Down Group 1, the ionisation energy:', 'Increases', 'First rises then falls', 'Stays constant', 'Decreases', 'D', 'Larger size and more shielding lower the ionisation energy down the group.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q06', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'When sodium reacts with water it produces NaOH and:', 'Oxygen', 'Hydrogen', 'Chlorine', 'Nitrogen', 'B', 'Sodium reacts with water to give sodium hydroxide and hydrogen gas.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q07', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'The solubility of Group 2 hydroxides down the group:', 'Stays constant', 'Decreases', 'Increases', 'Becomes zero', 'C', 'Group 2 hydroxide solubility increases down the group.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-s-block-q08', 'jee-chemistry-s-block', 'Washing soda is the common name for:', 'Sodium chloride', 'Sodium hydroxide', 'Sodium nitrate', 'Sodium carbonate', 'D', 'Sodium carbonate decahydrate is known as washing soda.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q01', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'The inert pair effect makes which oxidation state more stable for heavier p-block elements?', 'Higher state', 'Lower state', 'Zero state', 'Negative state', 'B', 'The inert pair effect stabilises the lower oxidation state for heavier members.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q02', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Which is the most reactive halogen?', 'Chlorine', 'Fluorine', 'Bromine', 'Iodine', 'B', 'Fluorine is the most reactive halogen and strongest oxidiser.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q03', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Nitrogen exists as a diatomic gas largely because of its strong:', 'Ionic bonds', 'Hydrogen bonds', 'Triple bond', 'Metallic bonds', 'C', 'Nitrogen forms a very strong triple bond, making N2 a stable diatomic gas.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q04', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Aluminium oxide is classified as a/an:', 'Amphoteric oxide', 'Basic oxide', 'Acidic oxide', 'Neutral oxide', 'A', 'Aluminium oxide is amphoteric, reacting with both acids and bases.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q05', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Which element shows the strongest tendency for catenation?', 'Silicon', 'Carbon', 'Nitrogen', 'Oxygen', 'B', 'Carbon shows the strongest catenation, giving the vast field of organic chemistry.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q06', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Across a period in the p-block, non-metallic character generally:', 'Increases', 'Decreases', 'Stays constant', 'Disappears', 'A', 'Non-metallic character rises across a period as effective nuclear charge increases.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q07', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'Noble gases are largely unreactive because they have:', 'One valence electron', 'Completely filled valence shells', 'Half-filled p orbitals', 'High electron affinity', 'B', 'Noble gases have completely filled valence shells, giving great stability.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-p-block-q08', 'jee-chemistry-p-block', 'The oxidising power of halogens follows the order:', 'F2 greater than Cl2 greater than Br2 greater than I2', 'I2 greater than Br2 greater than Cl2 greater than F2', 'Cl2 greater than F2 greater than Br2 greater than I2', 'Br2 greater than I2 greater than Cl2 greater than F2', 'A', 'Oxidising power decreases down the group: F2 greater than Cl2 greater than Br2 greater than I2.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q01', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Transition metals show variable oxidation states because of involvement of:', 'Both (n-1)d and ns electrons', 's orbitals only', 'p orbitals only', 'f orbitals only', 'A', 'Both (n-1)d and ns electrons can take part, giving variable oxidation states.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q02', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Most transition metal compounds are coloured due to:', 'd-d transitions', 's-p transitions', 'Nuclear reactions', 'Hydrogen bonding', 'A', 'Colour arises from d-d electronic transitions in partially filled d orbitals.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q03', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'The spin-only magnetic moment of an ion with two unpaired electrons is about:', '1.73 BM', '5.92 BM', '3.87 BM', '2.83 BM', 'D', 'Using the square root of n times n plus two with n equal two gives about 2.83 BM.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q04', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'The steady decrease in size across the lanthanides is called the:', 'Inert pair effect', 'Diagonal relationship', 'Lanthanide contraction', 'Shielding effect', 'C', 'Poor 4f shielding causes the lanthanide contraction across the series.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q05', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Which ion is colourless?', 'Cu two plus', 'Fe three plus', 'Zn two plus', 'Mn two plus', 'C', 'Zinc two plus has a fully filled d10 configuration, so it is colourless.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q06', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Potassium permanganate is a strong oxidiser with manganese in oxidation state:', 'Plus seven', 'Plus four', 'Plus six', 'Plus two', 'A', 'In KMnO4 manganese is in the plus seven oxidation state.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q07', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Paramagnetism in transition metal ions is due to:', 'Paired electrons', 'Nuclear spin', 'Filled orbitals', 'Unpaired electrons', 'D', 'Unpaired d electrons make many transition metal ions paramagnetic.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-d-f-block-q08', 'jee-chemistry-d-f-block', 'Compared with lanthanides, actinides show:', 'Fewer oxidation states', 'More oxidation states and radioactivity', 'No oxidation states', 'Only the plus two state', 'B', 'Actinides are radioactive and display a wider range of oxidation states.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q01', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'Which carbon-halogen bond is the weakest and most reactive?', 'C-F', 'C-Cl', 'C-Br', 'C-I', 'D', 'The C-I bond is the weakest, making iodoalkanes the most reactive.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q02', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'An SN2 reaction proceeds with:', 'Inversion of configuration', 'Retention of configuration', 'Racemisation', 'No change in geometry', 'A', 'SN2 proceeds through backside attack, giving inversion (Walden inversion).', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q03', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'The intermediate in an SN1 reaction is a:', 'Carbanion', 'Carbocation', 'Free radical', 'Carbene', 'B', 'SN1 proceeds through a planar carbocation intermediate.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q04', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'Which substrate reacts fastest by the SN1 mechanism?', 'Primary halide', 'Secondary halide', 'Tertiary halide', 'Methyl halide', 'C', 'Tertiary halides form the most stable carbocation, favouring SN1.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q05', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'Aryl halides are less reactive to nucleophilic substitution because of:', 'Partial double-bond character of the C-X bond', 'Weak C-X bonds', 'Low molar mass', 'High temperature', 'A', 'Resonance gives the C-X bond partial double-bond character, resisting substitution.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q06', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'By Saytzeff''s rule, elimination favours the alkene that is:', 'More substituted', 'Less substituted', 'Always terminal', 'Always cis', 'A', 'Saytzeff''s rule favours the more substituted, more stable alkene.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q07', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'A Grignard reagent has the general formula:', 'R-O-R', 'R-CHO', 'R-OH', 'R-MgX', 'D', 'A Grignard reagent is R-MgX, a powerful nucleophile made from a haloalkane.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes-q08', 'jee-chemistry-haloalkanes-haloarenes', 'The rate of an SN2 reaction depends on the concentration of:', 'Substrate only', 'Nucleophile only', 'Neither', 'Both substrate and nucleophile', 'D', 'SN2 is bimolecular, so its rate depends on both substrate and nucleophile concentrations.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q01', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Which is more acidic, phenol or ethanol?', 'Ethanol', 'Neither is acidic', 'Both equal', 'Phenol', 'D', 'Phenol is more acidic because the phenoxide ion is resonance-stabilised.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q02', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Oxidation of a primary alcohol first gives a/an:', 'Ketone', 'Ether', 'Ester', 'Aldehyde', 'D', 'A primary alcohol oxidises to an aldehyde, then further to a carboxylic acid.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q03', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'The Lucas test distinguishes alcohols by their:', 'Colour', 'Boiling point', 'Reaction speed with HCl/ZnCl2', 'Density', 'C', 'The Lucas test compares how fast alcohols react with HCl and zinc chloride.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q04', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'The Williamson synthesis is the best method to prepare:', 'Alcohols', 'Aldehydes', 'Ethers', 'Amines', 'C', 'The Williamson synthesis makes ethers from an alkoxide and a haloalkane.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q05', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Phenol gives which colour with neutral ferric chloride?', 'Violet', 'Yellow', 'Brown', 'Colourless', 'A', 'Phenol forms a violet coloured complex with neutral ferric chloride.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q06', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Which alcohol resists oxidation under mild conditions?', 'Primary', 'Secondary', 'All oxidise equally', 'Tertiary', 'D', 'A tertiary alcohol has no hydrogen on the carbinol carbon, so it resists mild oxidation.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q07', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Acid-catalysed dehydration of an alcohol gives a/an:', 'Alkene', 'Alkane', 'Acid', 'Ketone', 'A', 'Dehydration removes water to form an alkene by an E1 pathway.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers-q08', 'jee-chemistry-alcohols-phenols-ethers', 'Ethers are generally cleaved by hot:', 'Water', 'Ethanol', 'Sodium hydroxide', 'Hydroiodic acid', 'D', 'Ethers are fairly inert but are cleaved by hot hydroiodic acid.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q01', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'The carbonyl carbon undergoes which kind of reaction?', 'Nucleophilic addition', 'Electrophilic addition', 'Free-radical substitution', 'Elimination only', 'A', 'The electrophilic carbonyl carbon undergoes nucleophilic addition.', 0),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q02', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'Tollens'' reagent gives a silver mirror with:', 'Ketones', 'Ethers', 'Aldehydes', 'Alcohols', 'C', 'Aldehydes reduce Tollens'' reagent to a silver mirror; ketones do not.', 1),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q03', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'The aldol condensation requires the carbonyl compound to have a/an:', 'Alpha-hydrogen', 'Aromatic ring', 'Halogen', 'Nitro group', 'A', 'An alpha-hydrogen is needed to form the enolate in an aldol reaction.', 2),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q04', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'The Cannizzaro reaction occurs with aldehydes that lack a/an:', 'Carbonyl group', 'Double bond', 'Methyl group', 'Alpha-hydrogen', 'D', 'Aldehydes without an alpha-hydrogen undergo the Cannizzaro disproportionation.', 3),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q05', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'Which compound is the strongest acid?', 'Trichloroacetic acid', 'Acetic acid', 'Ethanol', 'Phenol', 'A', 'Three electron-withdrawing chlorines make trichloroacetic acid the strongest here.', 4),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q06', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'A positive iodoform test indicates the presence of a:', 'Carboxylic acid', 'Simple ether', 'Primary amine', 'Methyl ketone', 'D', 'Methyl ketones (and ethanal) give the yellow iodoform precipitate.', 5),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q07', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'Why are aldehydes more reactive than ketones toward nucleophiles?', 'Greater steric hindrance', 'Aromatic stabilisation', 'Higher molar mass', 'Less steric hindrance and less electron donation', 'D', 'Aldehydes have less steric crowding and less alkyl donation, so they react faster.', 6),
  ('jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids-q08', 'jee-chemistry-aldehydes-ketones-acids', 'The carboxylate ion is stabilised by:', 'Resonance over two oxygens', 'Hydrogen bonding only', 'A single localised charge', 'An aromatic ring', 'A', 'The negative charge is delocalised over two equivalent oxygens by resonance.', 7),
  ('jee-chemistry-amines-q01', 'jee-chemistry-amines', 'Amines are basic because nitrogen has a:', 'Vacant orbital', 'Lone pair of electrons', 'Positive charge', 'Triple bond', 'B', 'The lone pair on nitrogen accepts a proton, making amines basic.', 0),
